<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-343-546  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 343 546.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 12 1989 v8 n12 p152(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Navy delays IBM buys of more than $50K.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Karen K.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     United States. NavyGovernment ContractsInvestigationsComputer SystemsPurchases.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Navy Delays IBM Buys of More Than $50KandM;The Navy has delayed all service procurements involving IBM-compatiblesystems valued at more than $50,000.andM;The Department of the Navy ADP Acquisition Assessment Panel took the actionto give it time to assess the way the Navy buys ADP equipment, said Lt.andO;Bruce Cole, a Navy spokesman.andM;The delay will remain in effect until the panel completes its investigation,officials said.andM;&quot;It [the dalay] was designed to catch things that might not have been done ascarefully as they should have been,&quot; said Paula Davis, a member of the panel.andM;Six vendors complained in November to then-Defense Secretary Frank Carluccithat the Navy improperly favoredIBM in procurements.andP;  A spokesman for RearAdm.andP;  Paul Tobin, the Navy's information resources management director, saidthe panel set the $50,000 threshold because almost all the contracts cited bythe vendors exceeded that amount.andM;Rep.andP;  James J. Florio (D-N.J.), chairman of the House Energy and CommerceSub-committee on Commerce, Consumer Protection and Competitiveness, and Rep.andO;John Conyers Jr.andP;  (D-Mich.), chairman of the House Government OperationsCommittee, in December asked the DOD inspector general, the General ServicesAdministration and the General Accounting Office to investigate the allegedbias.andP;  The DOD inspector general's probe was halted in February because itduplicated the GAO's investigation.andM;A Navy official said Florio complained to then-Navy Secretary William Ballabout the termination of the inspector general's inquiry.andM;Ball established the panel in response to Florio's concerns, he said.andM;Tobin and Rear Adm.andP;  William Hauenstein chair the 10-member panel.andP;  Othermembers include various government and industry experts.andM;The Navy spokesman said all members of the panel have full-time jobs inaddition to their duties as panel members, and the amount the panel canaccomplish is &quot;a trade-off between workload, completeness and addressing theissues.&quot;andM;Navy official said they hope their investigation will end in midsummer, aboutthe time the Government Operations Committee plans to hold hearings on theissue.andO;</TEXT></DOC>